dencies**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether the \\\"git executable\\\" actually requires a deterministic setup, especially since TCK Ubuntu has git but no Docker image. There are risks, like assuming that git is available in the environment, and issues with GPG signing due to missing configuration. \\n\\nI should check if I need to cite specific resolved dependencies in the summary briefly. Regarding the inclusion of `org.apache.maven.scm:maven-scm-provider-gittest:1.11.1`, it seems unnecessary since it's an upstream test fixture. Is the \\\"optional Maven dependencies\\\" instruction clear? The POM lists this as a test dependency, and if the agent desires upstream TCK-style tests, I could consider adding testImplementation.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"No extra Maven dependencies or Docker service are needed; the artifact is a Git executable Maven SCM provider whose compile/runtime dependencies resolve transitively, but meaningful execution-style tests need a temporary local Git repository rather than a remote service.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"If tests execute provider commands instead of only constructing command lines or parsing consumers, create a temp Git repository with `git init`, configure local `user.name` and `user.email`, add/commit files as needed, and use local paths/file URLs. Do not rely on network remotes or signed tags; for `GitTagCommand.createCommandLine` in 1.11.1 pass the new `boolean sign` argument.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Execution-style coverage assumes the test environment has the `git` executable on PATH.\",\n    \"Remote Git operations and signed tags can be flaky or require credentials/GPG configuration; prefer local repositories and unsigned tags.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0d86caec653d2189016a2889b9552881969ca92949eea420d2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "o